<HEAD>``The Last Emperor'' Tops ``A Fish Called Wanda'' at Awards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, ``Michael Palin, with 1 graf to CORRECT details
of Palin's role. Pick up 8th pvs, ``It was</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Last Emperor,'' which swept last year's
Academy Awards, won this year's top British film award <DATE>Sunday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>,
while two stars from ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' won top acting awards.
   The Danish movie ``Babette's Feast'' won as best foreign language
film and <PERSON>Louis Malle</PERSON> took top directing honors for ``Au Revoir Les
Enfants.'' Both movies had also been nominated for best film of <DATE>1988</DATE>.
   Sir <PERSON>Alec Guinness</PERSON>, the 74-year-old veteran actor, received the
British Academy of Film and Television Arts' most prestigious award,
becoming a fellow of the academy. It was presented by Oscar-winning
director Sir <PERSON>David Lean</PERSON> instead of fellow director Sir <PERSON>Richard
Attenborough</PERSON>, who was hospitalized <DATE>Sunday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME> for suspected
kidney stones.
   Guinness, who won an Oscar for ``The Bridge on the River Kwai''
in <DATE>1957</DATE>, has been nominated for another Oscar this year for his
supporting role in ``Little Dorrit.'' The Academy Awards will be
presented in <LOCATION>Hollywood</LOCATION> on <DATE>March 29</DATE>.
   Comedian <PERSON>John Cleese</PERSON> was chosen best actor as the reserved
English lawyer who lost his inhibitions to an American woman thief,
played by <PERSON>Jamie Lee Curtis</PERSON>, in ``A Fish Called Wanda.''
   Cleese, accepting the award from actor <PERSON>Dudley Moore</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Los
Angeles</LOCATION>, said in a closed-circuit TV relay he thought it should have
gone to co-star <PERSON>Kevin Kline</PERSON>, who was also nominated for his role as
a manic jewel thief. Kline is nominated for an Oscar but <PERSON>Cleese</PERSON> is
not.
   <PERSON>Michael Palin</PERSON>, the movie's stuttering animal lover who was forced
to watch his goldfish swallowed and to accidentally cause the deaths
of several dogs, got the best supporting actor award.
   ``It was a marvelous film to work on _ except if you're a fish or
a dog,'' he joked in accepting the award. ``I want to thank <PERSON>John
Cleese</PERSON> who upgraded me from a pet salesman to a pet murderer and all
the doggies who gave their lives.''
   The <PERSON>Michael Balcon</PERSON> award for outstanding British contribution to
cinema went to <PERSON>Charles Crichton</PERSON>, director of ``A Fish Called Wanda''
and more than a score of other films.
   Two of <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s leading ladies walked off with the best actress
awards, <PERSON>Maggie Smith</PERSON> for her starring role as a spinster piano
teacher in <LOCATION>Dublin</LOCATION> in ``The Lonely Passion of <PERSON>Judith Hearne</PERSON>'' and
<PERSON>Dame Judi Dench</PERSON> for her supporting role as the pushy mother in ``A
Handful of Dust.'' Both are previous British award winners.
   <PERSON>Ms. Smith</PERSON> skipped the ceremony because of a broken shoulder.
   <PERSON>Bernardo Bertolucci</PERSON>, accepting the best picture award for his
epic film ``The Last Emperor'' about Chinese Emperor <PERSON>Pu Yi</PERSON>, praised
the important British contribution to the movie's technical and
acting success, including actor <PERSON>Peter O'Toole</PERSON>, who lost out in the
best supporting actor competition.
   ``A World Apart'' won for best original screenplay, ``The
Unbearable Lightness of Being'' for best adapted screenplay,
``Empire of the Sun'' for best score, and ``Defense Counsel <PERSON>Sedov</PERSON>,''
a Soviet movie about the righting of injustice, as best short film.
   The main Oscar nominees _ ``Rain Man,'' ``Dangerous Liaisons,''
``<LOCATION>Mississippi</LOCATION> Burning,'' ``The Accidental Tourist'' and ``Working
Girl'' _ were ineligible for the British awards because they were
not released in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> during <DATE>1988</DATE>.
   More than 2,300 people packed the grand ballroom at the <ORGANIZATION>Grosvenor
House Hotel</ORGANIZATION> for the ceremony. Actors <PERSON>Ben Kingsley</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Edward Fox</ORGANIZATION> and
actresses <PERSON>Shirley Maclaine</PERSON> and <PERSON>Hayley Mills</PERSON> were among the
celebrities who presented awards.
</TEXT>
