<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir <PERSON>David Lean</PERSON>, the 82-year-old director whose
films have won 27 <ORGANIZATION>Academy Awards</ORGANIZATION>, is planning to marry for the
sixth time, his lawyer said <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   Lean will wed 51-year-old interior designer <PERSON>Sandra Cooke</PERSON> before
<DATE>Christmas</DATE>, said attorney <PERSON>Michael Gee</PERSON>.
   The couple met five years ago in the frozen-food department of
Harrods department store where <PERSON>Ms. Cooke</PERSON> went up to Lean and asked
when his next film was due, said The Daily Mail's columnist <PERSON>Nigel
Dempster</PERSON>.
   Lean and <PERSON>Ms. Cooke</PERSON> were vacationing in <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>, Gee said. The
director's next film project will be an adaptation of <PERSON>Joseph
Conrad</PERSON>'s novel ``Nostromo.''
   Lean is the director of such classics as ``The Bridge on the
River Kwai,'' ``Lawrence of Arabia'' and ``Great Expectations.''
   ---
   <LOCATION>NEW YORK</LOCATION> (AP) - <ORGANIZATION>NBC</ORGANIZATION> newswoman <PERSON>Jane Pauley</PERSON>, who has interviewed
hundreds of celebrities, says she's still waiting to land an
elusive scoop: her husband, <PERSON>Garry Trudeau</PERSON>.
   ``I have thought about asking him,'' said <PERSON>Pauley</PERSON>, ``but a) he
would never do it, and b) I would not ultimately do it. But I know
it's a neat story.''
   Trudeau, the Pulitzer Prize-winning cartoonist, celebrates
<ORGANIZATION>Doonesbury</ORGANIZATION>'s <DATE>20th anniversary this month</DATE>.
   In an interview in the <DATE>Oct. 8</DATE> issue of People magazine, <ORGANIZATION>Pauley</ORGANIZATION>
said <PERSON>Trudeau</PERSON> believes that ``the more high profile you become, the
more you have to maintain it. And you have to adjust your life for
updates, just to keep everyone aware, which is time consuming.''
   But <ORGANIZATION>Pauley</ORGANIZATION> said someone should persuade <PERSON>Trudeau</PERSON> to do an
interview.
   ``It's not going to be me, but I'm just going to be really
irritated if it turns up on somebody else's network.''
   ---
</TEXT>
