<HEAD>War-Torn Sri Lanka Makes Great Locale for Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When <ORGANIZATION>Indiana Jones</ORGANIZATION> sought the <ORGANIZATION>Temple</ORGANIZATION>
of Doom in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, he was really doing it in <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION>. Likewise,
when Tarzan romped through the jungle he was not in <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> but near
the <LOCATION>Sri Lankan</LOCATION> hill town of <LOCATION>Kandy</LOCATION>.
   The late filmmaker Sir <PERSON>Carol Reed</PERSON> once referred to <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION> as
``the most natural and complete outdoor set,'' and this island
nation, despite its long war by Tamil militants for a separate
homeland, continues to lure American and British moviemakers.
   The fight by Tamil guerrillas for an independent nation for
their minority people broke out in <DATE>1983</DATE>. The Tamils, who are <PERCENT>18
percent</PERCENT> of the island's 16 million people, claim they are
discriminated against by the majority Sinhalese.
   Since <DATE>1980</DATE>, at least seven major films have been produced around
the lush mountains, dense jungles, rivers and waterfalls near
<LOCATION>Kandy</LOCATION>, barely a three-hour drive into the hills from the capital of
<LOCATION>Colombo</LOCATION>.
   Villages near <LOCATION>Kandy</LOCATION>, once the capital of a Buddhist kingdom,
have been villages everywhere from <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> in various
movies.
   ``<LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION> has managed to cheat as countries like <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Thailand</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON>Asoka Perera</PERSON>,
managing director of <ORGANIZATION>Sri Lanka Film Locations Limited</ORGANIZATION>.
   Perera's company helps scout locations for movies, and he said
<LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION>'s success in drawing filmmakers is due to a lack of red
tape involved in shooting here.
   One of the first major movies made in <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION> was in <DATE>1956</DATE> when
director <PERSON>David Lean</PERSON> filmed his hit movie ``Bridge on the River
Kwai'' on the island, then known as <ORGANIZATION>Ceylon</ORGANIZATION>. The film about British
POWs in <LOCATION>Burma</LOCATION> who are forced to build a bridge for the Japanese
during World War II, won six <ORGANIZATION>Academy Awards</ORGANIZATION>.
   The movie was set partly here, so when <PERSON>William Holden</PERSON> escaped a
Japanese prison on <LOCATION>Burma</LOCATION> and made his way through fierce jungle and
across sun-baked seas to a British base on <ORGANIZATION>Ceylon</ORGANIZATION>, he was really
just around the corner from where he started.
   Paramount's ``The Purple Plain'' with <PERSON>Gregory Peck</PERSON>, also about
the <LOCATION>Burma</LOCATION> campaign during World War II, and ``Elephant Walk''
starring <PERSON>Elizabeth Taylor</PERSON> in a movie about a <ORGANIZATION>Ceylon</ORGANIZATION> tea plantation,
were both made in <DATE>1954</DATE>.
   But <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION> lost out as a location for foreign movies from
1970-77 when the pro-socialist government led by the <ORGANIZATION>Sri Lankan
Freedom Party</ORGANIZATION> viewed anything coming from the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION> as decadent.
   It was not until <DATE>1980</DATE> that the trend was reversed when <PERSON>John
Derek</PERSON>'s ``Tarzan the Apeman'' was filmed starring his wife, <PERSON>Bo
Derek</PERSON>, and <PERSON>Richard Harris</PERSON>.
   Since then, movies shot in <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION> have included the <PERSON>George
Lucas-Steven Spielberg</PERSON> ``Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom'';
``Mountbatten _ the Last Viceroy''; ``Light Over the Water,'' which
was set partly in <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION>; ``Further Adventures of Tennessee
Buck,'' in which <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION> masquerades as <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION>; and ``Jungle
Heat,'' in which the country plays itself.
   ``Iron Triangle,'' about an American troop operation in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>,
completed production here in <DATE>February</DATE> and is to be released later
this year. It stars <ORGANIZATION>Beau Bridges</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Haing S. Ngor</PERSON>, who won an
<ORGANIZATION>Academy Award</ORGANIZATION> for supporting actor in <PERSON>Roland Joffe</PERSON>'s critically
acclaimed ``The Killing Fields.''
   <PERSON>Jayantha Jayatillaka</PERSON>, of <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION> Film Locations Limited, said
films made here earn the country needed foreign exchange and give a
boost to the tourist industry. Expenditures on filming in <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION>
were reported to be <MONEY>$8 million</MONEY> for ``Indiana Jones,'' <MONEY>$5 million</MONEY>
for ``Tarzan the Apeman'' and <MONEY>$3 million</MONEY> for ``Iron Triangle.
   <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION>'s mix of cultures also helps producers find ``extras''
for their projects, thus reducing their costs, <PERSON>Jayatillaka</PERSON> said.
   ``For the making of `<ORGANIZATION>Iron Triangle</ORGANIZATION>,' Sri Lankans of Chinese
descent and those who were descendants of traders from <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION>
were recruited to play Vietnamese,'' he said.
   But <LOCATION>Sri Lanka</LOCATION>'s ethnic conflict, born from that same cultural
mix, has blocked filming on some parts of the island, <PERSON>Perera</PERSON> said.
   ``Some of the scenes of `Tarzan the Apeman' were filmed at the
beaches in eastern <LOCATION>Trincomalee</LOCATION> district in <DATE>1980</DATE> before the violence
broke out,'' he said. ``Since <DATE>1983</DATE>, we have to stay clear of the
north and east despite the fact there are some beautiful locations
there.''
   But <PERSON>Perera</PERSON> said spectacular scenery and miles of palm-lined
beaches exist elsewhere on the island.
   The island is being considered for a movie about a journalist in
the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> during the overthrow of President <PERSON>Ferdinand Marcos</PERSON>.
   The movie's star, <PERSON>Rebecca Gilling</PERSON> of the Australian TV series
``Return to <ORGANIZATION>Eden</ORGANIZATION>,'' was recently in <LOCATION>Colombo</LOCATION> with producer <PERSON>Bob
Markowitz</PERSON>. Keeping with the international spirit of moviemaking
here, the production is being handled by an Australian company.
</TEXT>
