<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Hello dear. You're very handsome. Yes you are,''
Sir <PERSON>Alec Guinness</PERSON> coos through the cage at a rhinoceros.
   ``You've got a sweet face, very pretty ears,'' the elder
statesman of British acting says, as he strolls through <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>'s
central <PERSON>Zoologischen Garten</PERSON>.
   His chat with the animals is almost as engaging as the wonderful
characters he has portrayed on stage and screen during five decades
as one of the world's finest, most chameleon-like talents.
   On this particular day, the <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> Film Festival was awarding
the 73-year-old <ORGANIZATION>Guinness</ORGANIZATION> its special ``Ehren Bear'' (honorary bear)
for lifetime achievement in the cinema. The actor, however, elected
to avoid the morning crush of screenings and news conferences for a
romp in the zoo.
   ``I'm not actually that keen on them; I hate to see certain
animals caged up,'' he said.
   ``But I remember this zoo being small and very imaginatively
laid out on the open plan, and I thought it might be amusing to
have a second look.'' He last visited the <PERSON>Zoologischen Garten</PERSON> <DATE>14
years ago</DATE>.
   Images of some of the zoo's reported stock of 10,000 animals
have lingered: ``They used to have white rhinoceroses there that
were charming. And a great sea lion covered in shrapnel wounds _ an
old thing that was like a symbol of <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>; a splendid, great
creature.''
   This time around, <ORGANIZATION>Guinness</ORGANIZATION>' observations are as keen as ever,
whether applied to the varieties of zoo-bound species or the
special tributes that have marked his career.
   In <DATE>1980</DATE>, he received a special <ORGANIZATION>Academy Award</ORGANIZATION> to honor a range of
work encompassing such portrayals as the sinister <PERSON>Fagin</PERSON> in ``Oliver
Twist'' (<DATE>1948</DATE>), a comic octet of murder victims in ``Kind Hearts
and Coronets'' (<DATE>1950</DATE>), the hard-driving <PERSON>Colonel Nicholson</PERSON> in ``The
Bridge on the River Kwai'' (<DATE>1957</DATE>), the aging mystic <PERSON>Ben Obi-Wan
Kenobi</PERSON> in ``Star Wars'' (<DATE>1977</DATE>) and its sequels.
   Last year, he was twice feted in lavish galas _ in <DATE>April</DATE> at <LOCATION>New
York</LOCATION>'s Lincoln Center and in <DATE>May</DATE> at the <LOCATION>Cannes</LOCATION> Film Festival.
   The occasion in <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION> may be less tony, but its significance is
no less clear: in the <ORGANIZATION>Festival</ORGANIZATION>'s 38 years, <ORGANIZATION>Guinness</ORGANIZATION> is only the
second actor to be so honored, following <PERSON>James Stewart</PERSON> in <DATE>1982</DATE>.
   ``I'm afraid when you get rather elderly, these things seem to
come on you rather more than you might wish,'' he says, his brisk
gait belying his years, his nose becoming slightly red in the
seasonal chill.
   A signpost draws his attention: ``I think that way may be the
pheasantry. Do you mind if we go in there?''
   Somewhere between pheasants and finches, the conversation turns
to work. His latest project is ``Little Dorrit,'' the six-hour film
adaptation of <PERSON>Charles Dickens</PERSON>' novel in which he plays <PERSON>William
Dorrit</PERSON>, a long-term inmate of a debtor's prison who finds that
sudden wealth brings sudden freedom.
   Guinness had not performed <PERSON>Dickens</PERSON> since the <DATE>1940s</DATE>, when he both
adapted ``Great Expectations'' for the stage and made his movie
debut as <ORGANIZATION>Herbert Pocket</ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON>David Lean</PERSON>'s <DATE>1946</DATE> film version. He then
appeared in ``Oliver Twist'' in <DATE>1948</DATE>. He considers ``Little
Dorrit'' to be one of <PERSON>Dickens</PERSON>' two or three greatest novels.
   ``Dickens offers great temptations for actors because you can go
over the top,'' he said.
   Later this year, he'll be seen as <PERSON>Mr. Todd</PERSON> in a movie of <PERSON>Evelyn
Waugh</PERSON>'s <DATE>1934</DATE> novel, ``A Handful of Dust.'' Then there's Lee
Blessing's current Broadway play, ``A Walk in the <LOCATION>Woods</LOCATION>,'' which
<ORGANIZATION>Guinness</ORGANIZATION> may do on the <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> stage. He last trod the West End
boards in <PERSON>Alan Bennett</PERSON>'s ``The Old Country'' in <DATE>1977-8</DATE>.
   ``It's a very distinguished piece of writing,'' he says of the
play. But <ORGANIZATION>Guinness</ORGANIZATION> acknowledges its pitfalls, as well: ``The amount
of learning for a two-hander is horrendous. An actor's great fear
is that he won't have the memory.''
   On that topic, he is emboldened by the recent return to the
stage, after a decade away, of his friend and mentor, Sir <PERSON>John
Gielgud</PERSON>, in the new play ``The Best of Friends.''
   ``<PERSON>Gielgud</PERSON> is 83,'' <ORGANIZATION>Guinness</ORGANIZATION> says matter-of-factly, ``and he got
through it (the play) very successfully.''
   By now, the sky has clouded over, and rain looks likely.
Guinness has a lunch date for which he mustn't be late, so he
returns to his hotel to find that autograph hunters have arrived.
   ``There they are,'' he says, sounding resigned as the anonymity
of the walk in the zoo gives way to the fans' ever-ready pens and
cameras.
   But before leaving the zoo, he has one last remark about rhinos:
``We're told they have very nice personalities.''
   He takes an inimitable pause. ``But I don't think I'd like to
encounter them intimately.''
</TEXT>
