<HEAD>Oscar-Winning Epic Restored For Re-Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-six years after the premiere of ``Lawrence
of Arabia,'' the Oscar-winning epic will be re-released with scenes
that had been cut from the original and a new look and sound created
by a <MONEY>$600,000</MONEY> restoration.
   The re-edited ``Lawrence'' will be just as its director, <PERSON>David
Lean</PERSON>, intended.
   ```Lawrence of Arabia' was the first film I saw that made me want
to be a moviemaker,'' said director <PERSON>Steven Spielberg</PERSON>, a co-chairman
of the <ORGANIZATION>American Film Institute's National Center for Film</ORGANIZATION> and Video
Preservation.
   The film institute and <ORGANIZATION>Columbia Pictures</ORGANIZATION> announced the re-release
on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   The center will receive proceeds from a series of benefits at
which the restored film will premiere: <DATE>Feb. 4</DATE> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, <DATE>Feb. 5</DATE> in
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> and <DATE>Feb. 12</DATE> in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>.
   The 2{ years of work done on ``Lawrence of Arabia'' were ``the
most expensive, extensive and difficult film restoration ever
attempted,'' said <PERSON>Robert A. Harris</PERSON>, an archivist who conducted the
restoration for the institute.
   ``Lawrence of Arabia'' won Academy Awards for best picture,
director, color cinematography, color art direction, sound, editing
and music, but Lean's original editing plan was not followed in the
rush to get the movie ready in <DATE>1962</DATE>.
   Lean, 80, rerecorded lost parts of the original sound track with
<PERSON>Peter O'Toole</PERSON>, who starred as <ORGANIZATION>T.E. Lawrence</ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON>Alec Guinness</PERSON>, who
played King Faisal. New lines were added. Missing ones were redubbed.
   ``All of their voices have mellowed,'' <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> said, ``and so we
had to change the harmonics by using computers.''
   Existing prints of the film were in terrible shape, said <PERSON>Dawn
Steel</PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION>Columbia Pictures</ORGANIZATION>. She and filmmaker <PERSON>Martin
Scorsese</PERSON> are chairmen of the institute's film-preservation fund.
   ``Parts of the film had been cut and lost, and the color was
appalling,'' Steel said. ``But now the film looks brand new. The
color is perfect, and it's the cut that David Lean wanted.''
</TEXT>
