<HEAD>Olivier Led Illustrious Group of Honored Performers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Olivier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Laurence Olivier</PERSON> led a troupe of knights and dames
who had illustrious stage and screen careers, and his special status
was enhanced when he gained the title of baron.
   Olivier, who died <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, was knighted in <DATE>1947</DATE> and elevated in
<DATE>1970</DATE> to a peerage as <PERSON>Baron Olivier</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Brighton</LOCATION>. The title gave him a
seat in the <ORGANIZATION>House of Lords</ORGANIZATION>, which along with the <ORGANIZATION>House of Commons</ORGANIZATION>
constitutes <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION>. The only other theatrical peer is
actor and theater founder <PERSON>Bernard Miles</PERSON>.
   The first actor to be knighted was <PERSON>Henry Irving</PERSON>, so honored by
<ORGANIZATION>Queen Victoria</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1895</DATE>. <PERSON>Ellen Terry</PERSON>, his leading lady in a
partnership that dominated the <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> stage for 25 years, was made a
dame in <DATE>1925</DATE>.
   The honors gave the profession respectability and helped
eliminate the remains of a puritan prejudice against actors.
   Actors have continued to appear on the annual Honors Lists
announced by <ORGANIZATION>Buckingham Palace</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Donald Wolfit</PERSON>, one of this century's great actor-managers, was
knighted in <DATE>1957</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Noel Coward</PERSON>, the actor and playwright of ``Hay Fever'' and
``Blithe Spirit,'' was knighted in <DATE>1970</DATE> and actor <PERSON>Rex Harrison</PERSON> was
so honored this year.
   Among the other actor-knights no longer living are <PERSON>Ralph
Richardson</PERSON>, the ebullient, eccentric actor who regularly appeared
alongside <PERSON>Olivier</PERSON> and <PERSON>John Gielgud</PERSON>, who was knighted after World War
II.
   <PERSON>Michael Redgrave</PERSON> became patriarch of an acting dynasty whose
scions include <PERSON>Vanessa Redgrave</PERSON> and her daughters, <PERSON>Natasha</PERSON> and <PERSON>Joely
Richardson</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Sybil Thorndike</PERSON> was made a dame in <DATE>1931</DATE> in the midst of a long
and illustrious career in Shakespearean roles. Many of her later
roles were played opposite her husband, actor-director <PERSON>Lewis Casson</PERSON>,
who was knighted in <DATE>1945</DATE>.
   Other great dames have included <PERSON>Edith Evans</PERSON>, the peppery comic
actress best known as Lady Bracknell in ``The Importance of <LOCATION>Being
Earnest</LOCATION>,'' and <PERSON>Gladys Cooper</PERSON>, the fragile star who last appeared on
the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> stages in <PERSON>Enid Bagnold</PERSON>'s ``The Chalk
Garden'' more than 30 years ago.
   Many actor-knights work regularly despite advancing years.
   The 85-year-old <PERSON>Gielgud</PERSON> won a <DATE>1981</DATE> Oscar for ``Arthur,'' and was
seen on the West End stage in early <DATE>1988</DATE> in <PERSON>Hugh Whitemore</PERSON>'s ``The
Best of Friends.''
   <PERSON>Peggy Ashcroft</PERSON>, 81, graduated with <PERSON>Olivier</PERSON> in <DATE>1925</DATE> from <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>'s
<ORGANIZATION>Central School of Speech and Drama</ORGANIZATION>. She was a mainstay of the <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>
stage throughout her career, but found international fame after
almost 60 years with her performances in ``A Passage To <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'' on
film and ``The Jewel In the Crown'' on television.
   <PERSON>Wendy Hiller</PERSON> at 76 undertook a six-month <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> run in ``Driving
Miss Daisy,'' <PERSON>Alfred Uhry</PERSON>'s Pulitzer Prize-winning play.
   <PERSON>Alec Guinness</PERSON>, known internationally for such classic films as
``The Bridge on the River Kwai'' and ``Tunes of Glory,'' was
knighted in <DATE>1959</DATE>.
   More recently he became known to new audiences as Obi-Wan Kenobi
in <DATE>1977</DATE>'s ``Star Wars,'' and as <PERSON>John Le Carre</PERSON>'s self-effacing spy
<PERSON>George Smiley</PERSON> on television. Guinness' <DATE>1988</DATE> starring role in the
American play ``A Walk In the Woods'' was his first <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> stage
work in 10 years.
   <PERSON>Judi Dench</PERSON>, the latest dame, was honored in <DATE>1988</DATE> after a string
of critically acclaimed performances. She made her debut as a
director this year, winning praise for her production of
<ORGANIZATION>Shakespeare</ORGANIZATION>'s ``Much Ado About Nothing.''
</TEXT>
