<HEAD>Turner Gets Rights To Show Columbia Films on TNT, TBS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Turner Broadcasting System Inc.</ORGANIZATION> announced
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> it is paying for the right to show 1,000 feature films
owned by <ORGANIZATION>Columbia Pictures Television Inc.</ORGANIZATION> on its two cable
stations.
   Terms were not disclosed.
   The film library, which includes a variety of movies dating from
<DATE>1935</DATE> to <DATE>1983</DATE>, would be shown on <ORGANIZATION>Turner Network Television</ORGANIZATION> and
SuperStation WTBS.
   ``This package contains just the right mix of action-oriented
films and popular comedies to support TBS' continued growth in the
<DATE>1990s</DATE>,'' said <PERSON>Bob Levi</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>TBS</ORGANIZATION> executive vice president.
   The library is licensed for a two-year period that begins in
<DATE>January</DATE> and is subject to renewal.
   <ORGANIZATION>TNT</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>TBS</ORGANIZATION> will share rights to the titles, but company
officials said the majority of the films will air on <ORGANIZATION>TNT</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Turner</ORGANIZATION>'s
mostly-movie channel.
   Among the titles in the package are ``<PERSON>Kramer vs. Kramer</PERSON>,''
``Tootsie,'' ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' ``<PERSON>Mr. Smith</PERSON>
Goes to <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>'' and ``The Bridge on the River Kwai.''
   Turner's film library already includes the pre-1986 MGM films,
pre-1950 <ORGANIZATION>Warner Brothers</ORGANIZATION> films and a number of RKO titles.
</TEXT>
